[1] The Lahu does not know the Shan word for \'91cheroot, cigarillo,\'92 so he uses the Lahu periphrasis \'9a\'fa \uc0\u596 \u768 -\u603 \u769  \'91little tobacco\'92. He has some of the wrapped up (with other belongings) in a large package, in case it should prove necessary to show the Shan just what kind he wants, but he has not unwrapped it yet (see below, sentences 7 and 9). [Ironically enough, \u596 \u768 -\u603 \u769  may ultimately be a loanword from Shan itself (cf. Shan \u660 \'e8 \'91few\'92), though it is perhaps mangled beyond a Shan\'92s recognition.]\
[2] The words P\'ee-ch\uc0\u596 \u770  y\u596 \u770  \'e0\u660  \'91the Shan (said) to him\'92 are tacked onto the end of the sentence as an afterthought. Such inversions are common in colloquial Lahu.\
[3] The Shan now thinks he understands, and recoils in horror. The Lahu word \'9a\'fa \'91tobacco\'92 sounds something like the Shan [sh\uc0\u601 \u780 ] \'91tiger\'92. Perhaps the Shan understands the word \u596 \u768 -\u603 \u769  \'91little thing\'92 (see note 1); this would lend plausibility to his hypothesis that there was a \'91little tiger\'92 or tiger-cub in the Lahu\'92s package, since a big one would not fit. This is not essential to the story, however, since the sequence of vowels u-\u596 -\u603  in \'9a\'fa \u596 \u768 -\u603 \u769 , when rapidly pronounced, sounds very much like the schwa-vocalism of the Shan form.}